-- Infosys Leads Decline In India's Software Exporters as Sensex Index Slides
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-10-19T11:25:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-19/sterlite-advances-infosys-declines-as-india-s-sensitive-index-fluctuates.html
India’s benchmark stock index fell
to the lowest level in three weeks, led by software exporters
after International Business Machines Corp. reported a drop in
new contracts.  Infosys Technologies Ltd., the nation’s second-biggest
software-services exporter, retreated to a one-month low. IBM,
the world’s largest computer-services provider, yesterday said
service contracts dropped seven percent in its third quarter.
 Tata Consultancy Services Ltd . lost 1.4 percent.  “The valuations are not comfortable,” said  Kaushik Dani ,
a Mumbai-based fund manager with Peerless Mutual Fund, which
manages $322 million in assets. “Investors needed a reason to
book some profits as the run-up has been sharp.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s  Sensitive Index , or  Sensex ,
fell 185.76, or 0.9 percent, to 19,983.13 as of the 3:30 p.m.
close in Mumbai, its lowest since Sept. 29. The gauge has
dropped 3.4 percent over the past four days, retreating from its
highest close of 20,873.33 on Jan. 8, 2008. The index has gained
25 percent from its recent low on May 25.  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange lost
0.8 percent to 6,027.30. The  BSE 200 Index  retreated 0.7 percent
to 2,545.18.  Infosys dropped 3.1 percent to 3,010.2 rupees while larger
rival  Tata Consultancy Services Ltd.  fell 1.4 percent to 967.75
rupees. The Indian companies get most of their sales abroad. An
index of information technology companies was the biggest drag
among 10 industry groups in the MSCI Asia Pacific Index.  Global Funds  Global funds have been net buyers of Indian stocks for 33
trading days, the longest run of inflows in more than five years
since the 40-day period ended Aug. 9, 2005, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  Overseas  investors  bought a net  6.54 billion rupees  ($147.6
million) of Indian equities on Oct. 15, extending this year’s
record inflows to 1.07 trillion rupees, according to the
nation’s market regulator.  This year’s 15 percent rally makes the Sensex the best
performer among the world’s 10 biggest stock markets. Foreign
fund inflows have surged 67 percent this year, making the
benchmark the most expensive in Asia and among the BRIC markets
that also include Brazil, Russia and China.  To contact the reporter on this story:
